\subsection{Graphs and crystals} A graph is an ordered pair $X = (V,E)$ of disjoint sets $V$ and $E$ with two
maps $o:E\rightarrow V$ and $t:E\rightarrow V$. It is finite if both $V$ and $E$ are finite sets.  A geometric graph is $V\cup (E\times[0,1])/\sim$ where the equivalence relation $\sim$ is defined by $o(e) \sim (e,0), t(e) \sim (e,1)$. Let $X$ and $X_0$ be two geometric graphs and let $\pi:X\rightarrow X_0$ be a covering map. The graph $X$ is called an abelian covering space of  $X_0$ if  the deck transformation group is abelian.
An abstract  crystal $C$ is an infinite regular covering of a geometric graph $X$ over a finite graph $X_0$, with
free abelian deck transformation group. Every abstract crystal is obtained by choosing a subgroup $H$ of the homology group $H_1(X_0,\mathbb{Z})$ when $\frac{H_1(X_0,\mathbb{Z})}{H}$ is a free abelian group.
